{{alphabetical|T}} {{Subjects|Tax law}} {{status|25%}}

Lesson 10: Review of reading and pronunciation, subject pronouns, and verbs
===Vowels=== Greek has five vowel sounds, all vowels are pronounced nearer the English long rather than short: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | α | approximately as in ''ball'' (closer to ''father'' in a Boston accent) |- | ε | approximately as in ''bet'' |- | ι | as in ''beet'' |- | ο | approximately as in ''boat'' |- | ου | as in ''boot'' |- |}
Throughout this book, tables highlighted in this color have (or will eventually have) audio recordings to go with them.
{{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1ab}}
As you can see from these examples, many letters in the Greek alphabet look like their counterparts in English. There are multiple spellings for some of these sounds: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_no_audio_color}}" | ι, η, υ, οι, ει, and υι all sound alike. |- | ε and αι sound like EH as in "kettle". |- | ο and ω sound like OH as in "over". |}
===Consonants=== The following letters sound like the English letters they resemble: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_no_audio_color}}" | κ, τ |}
''Note: If you're a native English speaker, try to pronounce a plain τ, that is '''without''' the "h" sound in the end.''
Reading practice: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | τα, τι, η, τη, το, του, τω, κάτω, κότα, άκου |}
Most Greek words have a stressed syllable which in words of more than one syllable is shown with an accent over the stressed vowel.
Vocabulary: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | κακό | bad |- | κατά | against, according to, toward |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1c}}
The following Greek consonants sound like familiar sounds from English, but look different from their English counterparts: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_no_audio_color}}" *β vee
*λ elle
*π pee
*δ the
*μ emm
*σ,ς ess
*ζ zee
*ν enn
*φ fee
*θ theh
*ξ eks
*ψ eeps
{|The letter sigma, σ, is written as ς at the end of a word. Some Greek speakers pronounce the sigma sound so that it sounds half-way between s and sh.
Vocabulary and reading practice: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | ναι | yes |- | καλό | good |- | πού | where |- | με | with |- | από | from |- | σε | in |- | αλλά | but |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1d}}
The following Greek consonants have sounds not found in English: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_no_audio_color}}" | γ | a soft, gargling g sound, except before the sounds ε and ι, where it sounds like y |- | ρ | like Spanish r |- | χ | like the ch in Scottish ''loch'' |- |}
Vocabulary and reading practice: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | γράφω | I write |- | για | for |- | γιατί | why?, because |- | προς | to, toward |- | όχι | no |- | παρακαλώ | please |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1e}}
The following combinations of letters have sounds that have to be learned: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_no_audio_color}}" | ου | oo |- | αυ | av before vowel or voiced consonant, else af |- | ευ | ev before vowel or voiced consonant, else ef |- | ηυ | iv before vowel or voiced consonant, else if |- | μπ | b at the beginning of a word, mb elsewhere |- | ντ | d at the beginning of a word, nd elsewhere |- | χε, χαι | heh |- | κε, και | keh |- |}
Vocabulary and reading practice: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | και | and |- | ή | or |- | αυτός | he |- | αύριο | tomorrow |- | ευχαριστώ | I give thanks, thank you (~"Eucharist") |- | γυρεύω | I look for |- | μπορώ | I can |- | χαίρετε | Rejoice! (a greeting and leave-taking) |- | καλοκαίρι | summer |- |}
One of the big obstacles for an English speaker trying to learn Greek is that so few common usage words are related to English ones (although an estimated 10% to 20% of the total English vocabulary has Greek roots, most of it though of scientific/technical nature). However, sometimes there is a relationship that would help you to remember the Greek word, but the relationship isn't obvious, as with ευχαριστώ and Eucharist. When this happens, we'll note it as in the example above, with ~. This may mean that the English word is derived from the Greek one, or merely that both the English word and the Greek one come from a common root.
Names of the letters: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | α | άλφα | ι | γιώτα (or ιώτα) | ρ | ρω (or ρο) |- | β | βήτα | κ | κάππα (or κάπα) | σ | σίγμα |- | γ | γάμμα | λ | λάμδα (or λάμβδα) | τ | ταυ |- | δ | δέλτα | μ | μι | υ | ύψιλον |- | ε | έψιλον | ν | νι | φ | φι |- | ζ | ζήτα | ξ | ξι | χ | χι |- | η | ήτα | ο | όμικρον | ψ | ψι |- | θ | θήτα | π | πι | ω | ωμέγα |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1g}}
===Personal subject pronouns=== Greek has three genders: masculine, feminine, and neuter. Here are the personal subject pronouns: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | εγώ | I | εμείς | we |- | εσύ | you, singular | εσείς | you, plural |- | αυτός | he | αυτοί | they (masculine) |- | αυτή | she | αυτές | they (feminine) |- | αυτό | it | αυτά | they (neuter) |- |} The second-person plural is also used as the formal form of address, even when speaking to a single person.
{{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1h}}
===Verbs===
====First conjugation==== The subject pronouns are usually omitted, because the form of the verb indicates the subject. For example: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_no_audio_color}}" | γράφω | I write |- | γράφεις | you (singular) write |- | γράφει | he/she/it writes |- | γράφουμε | we write |- | γράφετε | you (plural) write |- | γράφουν | they write |- |} There is no infinitive in modern Greek. For naming a verb, the first-person singular of the present tense is used as a generic term. For example, we refer to the verb γράφω, ''to write.''
To summarize the conjugation of a verb, we write it in a table like this: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | γράφω | γράφουμε |- | γράφεις | γράφετε |- | γράφει | γράφουν |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1i}}
Γράφω is an example of a verb belonging to the first conjugation. Verbs in this conjugation can be recognized because their accent falls before the final ω.
The following verbs belong to the first conjugation:
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | δίνω | give (~"donate") |- | αλλάζω | change |- | διαβάζω | read |- | κοιτάζω | look at |- | βλέπω | see |- | ακούω | hear (~"acoustic") |- | φτάνω | arrive |- | φεύγω | leave |- | παίρνω | take |- | αγοράζω | buy |- | ξέρω | know |- | νομίζω | think |- | βάζω | put |- | πίνω | drink |}
Vocabulary: {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1i2}}
Conjugations of some of these verbs: {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1i3}}
====The verbs έχω, ''to have,'' and είμαι, ''to be''==== Two important verbs are έχω, ''to have,'' and είμαι, ''to be.'' The first-conjugation verb έχω is regular in the present tense, so it has the same endings as γράφω.
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | έχω | έχουμε |- | έχεις | έχετε |- | έχει | έχουν |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1j}}
''To be'' in English is expressed in the active voice, but the Greek είμαι is passive, and doesn't have an active form. The ending -μαι is a typical, regular ending for passive verbs. Although we won't be concerned with passive constructions until later, είμαι is so important that you need to get it under your belt right away.
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | είμαι | είμαστε |- | είσαι | είστε |- | είναι | είναι |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1k}}
===Capital letters===
Now that we're ready to handle complete sentences, we need capital letters. Most of the capital letters of the Greek alphabet are similar in form either to the lowercase letters, or to their counterparts in the Latin alphabet:
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_no_audio_color}}" | α | Α | ι | Ι | ρ | Ρ |- | β | Β | κ | Κ | σ | Σ |- | γ | Γ | λ | Λ | τ | Τ |- | δ | Δ | μ | Μ | υ | Υ |- | ε | Ε | ν | Ν | φ | Φ |- | ζ | Ζ | ξ | Ξ | χ | Χ |- | η | Η | ο | Ο | ψ | Ψ |- | θ | Θ | π | Π | ω | Ω |- |}
===Sentences=== The order of words in a Greek sentence is much more free than in English, but you can correctly construct a sentence using the familiar English syntax of subject+verb, or subject+verb+object. The subject is usually omitted when it is a pronoun.
Sentences: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Είναι καλό. | It is good. |- | Είναι κακό. | It is bad. |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1l}}
In Greek, adjectives change their endings to agree with the gender and number of the nouns they describe (''declension''). The following vocabulary list introduces some nouns that happen to be neuter, and some adjectives, which are given in neuter form. The word το is the definite article, like English "the," used with singular neuter nouns.
Vocabulary: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | νερό | water |- | κρασί | wine |- | τσάι | tea |- | καυτό | hot |- | κρύο | cold |- | άσπρο | white |- | κόκκινο | red |- | θέλω | to want |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1m}}
Sentences: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Το νερό είναι κρύο. | The water is cold |- | Το κρασί είναι κρύο. | The wine is cold. |- | Το τσάι είναι καυτό. | The tea is hot. |- | Το άσπρο κρασί είναι κρύο. | The white wine is cold. |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1n}}
Negatives are formed by placing ''δεν'' before the verb. The question mark in Greek is the semicolon.
Sentences: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Το κόκκινο κρασί δεν είναι κρύο. | The red wine is not cold |- | Το νερό δεν είναι καυτό. | The water is not hot. |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1o}}
Dialog: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Χαίρετε. | Hello. |- | Χαίρετε. | Hello. |- | Έχετε τσάι; | Do you have tea? |- | Οχι, δεν έχουμε τσάι. Θέλετε νερό; | No, we don't have tea. Do you want water? |- | Ναι, ευχαριστώ. | Yes, thank you. |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1p}}
=== Dialogue 1 === ''Greeting others''
Mark: Γεια σας. Anna: Kαλημέρα. Mark: Τι κάνετε; Anna: Πολύ καλά και εσείς; Mark: Πολύ καλά.
==== Vocabulary ==== {| |- |'''Γειά σας'''||Hello! |- |'''Kαλημέρα'''||Good morning |- |'''Τι κάνετε'''||How are you? |- |'''Πολύ καλά'''||Very well |- |'''Και εσείς'''||And you? |}
=== Dialogue 2 === ''Introducing yourself''
Mark: Πώς σε λέvε; Anna: Mε λέvε Άvvα.
==== Vocabulary ==== {| |- |'''Πως'''||How |- |'''σε λένε'''|| they call you |- |'''με λένε'''|| they call me |- |}
===Summary of the alphabet and pronunciation=== ====Alphabet / Αλφάβητο==== The '''Greek Language''' was one of the first written languages in all world. The [[w:Script|script]] used had some peculiarities not observed today: for instance, the vowels were not written, and one needed to guess or to know their specific place inside the word. This alphabet has been evolving, through contact with other cultures and through the simple action of the time, until it became what it is today. Amongst the Greek alphabet, we can spot some (or even many) similarities with the [[w:Latin alphabet|Latin (or Roman) one]]. The alphabet used nowadays has 24 letters: 7 vowels and 17 consonants.
{| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; {{Greek clr}} border:1px #0066CC solid;" align="center" ! width="100" | Letter ! width="100" | English Name ! width="100" | Greek Name |- | align="center" | A a || align="center" | alpha || align="center" | άλφα |- | align="center" | Β β || align="center" | beta|| align="center" | βήτα |- | align="center" | Γ γ || align="center" | gamma|| align="center" | γάμμα |- | align="center" | Δ δ || align="center" | delta|| align="center" | δέλτα |- | align="center" | Ε ε || align="center" | epsilon|| align="center" | έψιλον |- | align="center" | Ζ ζ || align="center" | zeta|| align="center" | ζήτα |- | align="center" | Η η || align="center" | eta || align="center" | ήτα |- | align="center" | Θ θ || align="center" | theta || align="center" | θήτα |- | align="center" | Ι ι || align="center" | iota || align="center" | ιώτα |- | align="center" | Κ κ || align="center" | kappa || align="center" | κάπα |- | align="center" | Λ λ || align="center" | lambda || align="center" | λάμδα |- | align="center" | Μ μ || align="center" | mu || align="center" | μι |- | align="center" | Ν ν || align="center" | nu || align="center" | νι |- | align="center" | Ξ ξ || align="center" | ksi || align="center" | ξι |- | align="center" | Ο ο || align="center" | omicron || align="center" | όμικρον |- | align="center" | Π π || align="center" | pi || align="center" | πι |- | align="center" | Ρ ρ || align="center" | rho || align="center" | ρω |- | align="center" | Σ σ* || align="center" | sigma || align="center" | σίγμα |- | align="center" | Τ τ || align="center" | tau || align="center" | ταυ |- | align="center" | Υ υ || align="center" | ypsilon || align="center" | ύψιλον |- | align="center" | Φ φ || align="center" | phi || align="center" | φι |- | align="center" | Χ χ || align="center" | chi || align="center" | χι |- | align="center" | Ψ ψ || align="center" | psi || align="center" | ψι |- | align="center" | Ω ω || align="center" | omega || align="center" | ωμέγα |- | colspan="3" width="300"| * The sigma has a special lowercase form, used only at the end of words. Both lowercase sigmas have the same value. |}
Besides the alphabet, there is also an accent ( ´ ) and a diaeresis( ¨ ). The use of these two [[w:Diacritic|diacritics]] is discussed in the [[Greek: Phonology|next section]].
====Pronunciation of the Alphabet==== Greek sounds are, in general, soft. As a major rule, each letter carries a single sound (this is not universal, but almost, as we'll see later in this page). As in the [[Greek: Alphabet|previous chapter]], we see here a table with the various letters. This time, the columns represent not the name, but the ''approximate'' sound of the letters.
{| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; {{Greek clr}} border:1px #0066CC solid;" align="center" ! width="100" | Letter ! width="210" | How to say it ! width="75" | [[w:IPA|IPA]] ! width="75" | [[w:XSAMPA|XSAMPA]] |- | align="center" | A α || align="center" | '''a'''rc | align="center" | [[w:Open front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[a]}}]] || align="center" | a |- | align="center" | Β β || align="center" | '''v'''acuum | align="center" | [[w:Voiced labiodental fricative|{{IPA|[v]}}]] || align="center" | v |- | align="center" | Γ γ || align="center" | '''y'''''es'' before certain vowels, otherwise like Spanish ''a'''g'''ua'' | align="center" | [[w:Voiced palatal fricative|{{IPA|[&#669;]}}]] before [[w:Open-mid front unrounded vowel#Mid front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[&#603;]}}]] or [[w:Close front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]]; [[w:Voiced velar fricative|{{IPA|[&#611;]}}]] otherwise || align="center" | G |- | align="center" | Δ δ || align="center" | '''th'''is | align="center" | [[w:Voiced dental fricative|{{IPA|[&#240;]}}]] || align="center" | D |- | align="center" | Ε ε || align="center" | b'''e'''d | align="center" | [[w:Open-mid front unrounded vowel#Mid front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[&#603;]}}]] || align="center" | E |- | align="center" | Ζ ζ || align="center" | '''z'''oo | align="center" | [[w:Voiced alveolar fricative|{{IPA|[z]}}]] || align="center" | z |- | align="center" | Η η || align="center" | s'''ee''' | align="center" | [[w:Open-mid unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]] || align="center" | i |- | align="center" | Θ θ || align="center" | '''th'''in | align="center" | [[w:Voiceless dental fricative|{{IPA|[&#952;]}}]] || align="center" | T |- | align="center" | Ι ι || align="center" | s'''ee''' | align="center" | [[w:Close front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]] || align="center" | i |- | align="center" | Κ κ || align="center" | '''c'''''ute'' before certain vowels, else kno'''ck''' | align="center" | [[w:Voiceless palatal plosive|{{IPA|[c]}}]] before [[w:Open-mid front unrounded vowel#Mid front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[&#603;]}}]] or [[w:Close front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]]; [[w:Voiceless velar plosive|{{IPA|[k]}}]] otherwise || align="center" | c, k |- | align="center" | Λ λ || align="center" | c'''l'''ock | align="center" | [[w:Alveolar lateral approximant|{{IPA|[l]}}]] || align="center" | l |- | align="center" | Μ μ || align="center" | '''m'''ine | align="center" | [[w:Bilabial nasal|{{IPA|[m]}}]] || align="center" | m |- | align="center" | Ν ν || align="center" | '''n'''ine | align="center" | [[w:Alveolar nasal|{{IPA|[n]}}]] || align="center" | n |- | align="center" | Ξ ξ || align="center" | e'''xc'''ellent | align="center" | {{IPA|[ks]}} || align="center" | k_s |- | align="center" | Ο ο || align="center" | '''oh''' | align="center" | [[w:Open-mid back rounded vowel#Mid back rounded vowel|{{IPA|[&#596;]}}]] || align="center" | O |- | align="center" | Π π || align="center" | a'''p'''e | align="center" | [[w:Voiceless bilabial plosive|{{IPA|[p]}}]] || align="center" | p |- | align="center" | Ρ ρ || align="center" | like Spanish ''pe'''r'''o'' | align="center" | [[w:Alveolar flap|{{IPA|[ɾ]}}]] || align="center" | 4 |- | align="center" | Σ σ || align="center" | '''s'''oup | align="center" | [[w:Voiceless alveolar fricative|{{IPA|[s]}}]] || align="center" | s |- | align="center" | Τ τ || align="center" | ha'''t'''e | align="center" | [[w:Voiceless alveolar plosive|{{IPA|[t]}}]] || align="center" | t |- | align="center" | Υ υ || align="center" | s'''ee''' | align="center" | [[w:Close front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]] || align="center" | i |- | align="center" | Φ φ || align="center" | '''ph'''oto | align="center" | [[w:Voiceless labiodental fricative|{{IPA|[f]}}]] || align="center" | f |- | align="center" | Χ χ || align="center" | like German ''i'''ch''''' before certain vowels, else like German ''Lo'''ch''''' | align="center" | [[w:Voiceless palatal fricative|{{IPA|[ç]}}]] before [[w:Open-mid front unrounded vowel#Mid front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[&#603;]}}]] or [[w:Close front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]]; [[w:Voiceless velar fricative|{{IPA|[x]}}]] otherwise || align="center" | C, x |- | align="center" | Ψ ψ || align="center" | ma'''ps''' | align="center" | {{IPA|[ps]}} || align="center" | p_s |- | align="center" | Ω ω || align="center" | '''oh''' | align="center" | [[w:Open-mid back rounded vowel#Mid back rounded vowel|{{IPA|[&#596;]}}]] || align="center" | O |}
'''Note''': The letter Γγ is the most difficult to pronounce for an English speaker: it is like a stronger '''h''', simultaneous with the vibration of the vocal cords; in other words, it is the voiced counterpart of the '''χ'''. Before '''e''' and '''i''' vowels, it is pronounced as a '''y''' like in the word '''y'''es.
====Diphthongs==== ''[[w:Diphthongs|Diphthongs]]'' are combinations of two vowels that function as a unique sound. Note that in Modern Greek, the word ''Diphthong'' (δίφθογγος) is also used for combination of vowels that sound like a simple vowel. There are eight diphthongs in Modern Greek. There are also some similar combinations of consonants:
{| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; {{Greek clr}} border:1px #0066CC solid;" align="center" |+ '''Tabela II''' - Diphthongs ! width="100" | Diphthong ! width="300" | How to say it ! width="75" | IPA ! width="75" | XSAMPA |- | align="center" | αι || align="center" | b'''e'''d | align="center" | [[w:Open-mid front unrounded vowel#Mid front unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[&#603;]}}]] || align="center" | E |- | align="center" | αυ || align="center" | h'''av'''e before certain letters, '''af'''ter before others | align="center" | {{IPA|[av]}}, {{IPA|[af]}} || align="center" | av, af |- | align="center" | ει || align="center" | s'''ee''' | align="center" | [[w:Open-mid unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]] || align="center" | i |- | align="center" | ευ || align="center" | '''ev'''er before certain letters, '''ef'''fect before others | align="center" | {{IPA|[&#603;v]}}, {{IPA|[&#603;f]}} || align="center" | Ev, Ef |- | align="center" | ηυ || align="center" | '''ev'''ening before certain letters, b'''eef''' before others | align="center" | {{IPA|[iv]}}, {{IPA|[if]}} || align="center" | iv, if |- | align="center" | οι || align="center" | s'''ee''' | align="center" | [[w:Open-mid unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]] || align="center" | i |- | align="center" | ου || align="center" | s'''oo'''n | align="center" | [[w:Close back rounded vowel|{{IPA|[u]}}]] || align="center" | u |- | align="center" | υι || align="center" | s'''ee''' | align="center" | [[w:Open-mid unrounded vowel|{{IPA|[i]}}]] || align="center" | i |- | align="center" | γγ || align="center" | fi'''ng'''er | align="center" | [[w:Velar nasal|{{IPA|[&#331;}}]]g] || align="center" | Ng |- | align="center" | γκ || align="center" | '''g'''ood at the beginning of words, fi'''ng'''er anywhere else | align="center" | [[w:Voiced velar plosive|{{IPA|[g]}}]], [[w:Velar nasal|{{IPA|[&#331;}}]]g] || align="center" | g, Ng |- | align="center" | μπ || align="center" | '''b'''anana at the beginning of words, thu'''mb''' anywhere else | align="center" | [[w:Voiced bilabial plosive|{{IPA|[b]}}]], [mb] || align="center" | b, mb |- | align="center" | ντ || align="center" | '''d'''ay at the beginning of words, sa'''nd''' anywhere else | align="center" | [[w:Voiced dental plosive|{{IPA|[d]}}]], [nd] || align="center" | d, nd |}
====Accent and Diaeresis==== Most Greek words have a ''stressed syllable'' which is the syllable said with more strength: for instance, in the English words ''comfort'' and ''peculiarity'', the stressed syllables are ''com'' and ''ar'', respectively.
Greek marks the stressed syllable with an '''accent''' mark ( ΄ ) over the vowel. In one-syllable words, the accent is usually omitted. When the stress falls on a syllable that has a diphthong, the accent is used above the last letter of this diphthong. Thus, words like Παύλος (''Paul'') ou γυναίκα (''woman''), are correctly accented.
If the accent is put on the first vowel of a diphthong, it is not read as a diphthong but read as two independent vowels, as in the word ρολόι (''watch'' or ''clock''), which has three syllables, not two. On the other hand, if one wishes to separate the diphthong, but the accent falls on other syllable, the '''diaeresis''' ( ¨ ) is used, as in the word Εβραϊκός (''Hebrew'').
There are, however, some words that aren't stressed (usually monosyllabic grammatical words), and these don't have an accent. Words like these are read as affixes added to the main word. '''Examples''': *'''ο (''the'' masc.)''' "Ο πατέρας" (''The father'') is read as a single word - ''aw-pah-TE-ras''; *'''μου (''my'')''', "Ο πατέρας μου" (''My father'') is also read as a single word - ''aw-pa-TE-raz-mu''.
Every stressed word with more than one syllable carries an accent. However, there are monosyllabic words that also have accent, like ή (''or'') and πού (''where''). This accent has a double function: *It distinguishes words that, otherwise, would be equal - η (''the'' fem.) and που (''that, which''); *It marks words as strong, unlike their weak comparing counterparts.
[[Category:Modern Greek]] {{Modern Greek}}

{{expand}}
Western Music History can be traced back to Medieval times, with the Introduction of Chanting (later termed Gregorian Chanting) into the Catholic church services. Western Music then started becoming more of an art form with the advances in music notation and more focus on secular themes that occurred in the Renaissance period. We then have expansions of range and complexity as we move into the Baroque era. The Classical era gives us the emotional power associated with such composers as Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. Romanticism then transforms the rigid styles and forms of the Classical era into more individualistic stylizations. Tonality was at its peak during this period, then Impressionist music paved the way to the use of extreme dissonances in the music of the Modern era. This process continued into the current Contemporary period of music.
== Table of contents == #[[/Medieval Music/]] (476 A.D. to 1400 A.D.) #[[/Renaissance Music/]] (1400 A.D. to 1600 A.D.) #[[/Baroque Music/]] (1600 A.D. to 1750 A.D.) #[[/Classical Music/]] (1750 A.D. to 1820 A.D.) #[[/Romantic Music/]] (1820 A.D. to 1900 A.D.) #[[/Modern Music/]] (1900 A.D. to 1960 A.D.) #[[/Contemporary Music/]] (1945 A.D. to present)
== A Note Time Periods == There is no clear line when the Renaissance began and the Middle Ages ended. For western art music, there is no clear dividing point - the Renaissance in music happened at different times in different places. So for convenience, we will use 1400 A.D. as the start of the Renaissance.
